{{Lunisolar March}} '''Lunisolar March''' (旧暦三月) is the third {{ill|Month (Calendar)|ja|月 (暦)|lt=Month|lt_ja=月|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} of the year in the {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}).
Under definitions preceding the {{ill|Tenpō Calendar|ja|天保暦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, March was defined as the month that includes {{ill|Grain Rain|ja|穀雨|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the {{ill|New Calendar|ja|新暦|1=New Calendar (Japan)|lt=New Calendar|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, it corresponds approximately to late {{ill|March|ja|3月|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} to early {{ill|May|ja|5月|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Another name for March is {{nihongo|'''Yayoi'''|やよい}}. The origin of the name is explained in {{ill|March|ja|3月|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. An alternative name is “{{nihongo|'''Kishun'''|きしゅん}}”.
In the Eastern lunisolar calendar, the number of days in a month, known as {{ill|Large and Small|ja|大小|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (with large months having 30 days and small months 29 days), varies from year to year; consequently, some years have March ending on the 29th, with no March 30th.
