{{Lunisolar March|qq=}} '''Lunisolar March''' (旧暦三月) is the third {{ill|Month (Calendar)|ja|月 (暦)|lt=Month|lt_ja=月|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Month (Calendar)|qq=}} of the year in the {{ill|Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=}} ({{ill|Lunisolar calendar|ja|太陰太陽暦|1=Lunisolar calendar|2=ja|3=太陰太陽暦|comment=note that this is not the Japanese lunisolar calendar it is any lunisolar calendar|4=ru|5=Лунно-солнечный календарь|6=de|7=Lunisolarkalender|8=es|9=Calendario lunisolar|10=fr|11=Calendrier luni-solaire|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lunisolar calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Lunisolar calendar|qq=}}).
Under definitions preceding the {{ill|Tenpō Calendar|ja|天保暦|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō Calendar|qq=}}, March was defined as the month that includes {{ill|Grain Rain|ja|穀雨|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Grain Rain|qq=}}. In the {{ill|New Calendar|ja|新暦|1=New Calendar (Japan)|lt=New Calendar|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/New Calendar (Japan)|qq=}}, it corresponds approximately to late {{ill|March|ja|3月|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/March|qq=}} to early {{ill|May|ja|5月|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/May|qq=}}.
Another name for March is {{nihongo|'''Yayoi'''|やよい|qq=}}. An alternative name is “{{nihongo|'''Kishun'''|きしゅん|qq=}}”.
In the Eastern lunisolar calendar, the number of days in a month, known as {{ill|Large and Small|ja|大小|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Large and Small|qq=}} (with large months having 30 days and small months 29 days), varies from year to year; consequently, some years have March ending on the 29th, with no March 30th.
==Etymology of traditional Japanese name== {{afc comment|1=content here taken from [[:ja:3月]][[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 00:24, 11 May 2025 (UTC)}} [[File:2014-04-11 Kawashiro-keikoku 川代公園・川代渓谷DSCF6266.jpg|thumb|260px|right|{{ill|cherry blossom|ja|サクラ|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/cherry blossom|qq=}} ({{ill|Kawashiro Gorge|ja|川代渓谷|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawashiro Gorge|qq=}}’s {{ill|Somei Yoshino|ja|ソメイヨシノ|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Somei Yoshino|qq=}})]] In {{ill|Japan|ja|日本|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan|qq=}}, besides '''Yayoi''' (やよい) there are alternate names such as '''Flower month''' (花月), '''Auspicious month''' (嘉月), '''Flower-viewing month''' (花見月; はなみづき), '''Dream-viewing month''' (夢見月; ゆめみつき), '''Cherry blossom month''' (桜月; さくらづき, Lunisolar)<ref>{{Kotobank|桜月|デジタル大辞泉}}</ref>, and '''Late spring''' (暮春; ぼしゅん).
In Japan, this month is famous as the period of the {{ill|fiscal year|ja|年度|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/fiscal year|qq=}} change (primarily the {{ill|fiscal year|ja|会計年度|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/fiscal year|qq=}} and the {{ill|school year|ja|学年|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/school year|qq=}}). Throughout the month, {{ill|graduation ceremony|ja|卒業式|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/graduation ceremony|qq=}} and {{ill|farewell party|ja|送別会|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/farewell party|qq=}} are held, marking a time of meetings and partings. Also, at the end of the month corresponding to {{ill|spring break|ja|春休み|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/spring break|qq=}}, {{ill|personnel transfer|ja|人事異動|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/personnel transfer|qq=}} take place, and many schools, companies, or {{ill|government office|ja|官公庁|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/government office|qq=}} become busy with moving, transitions, and the start of new life.
In the Asahikawa dialect of the {{ill|Hokkaido Ainu language|ja|北海道アイヌ語|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkaido Ainu language|qq=}}, March is called “Toetanne” (トエタンネ; {{ill|Ainu language|ja|アイヌ語|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ainu language|qq=}}: toetanne), meaning “long days,” <ref>[https://ainugo.nam.go.jp/siror/monthly/201510.html#01 《ことばからみたアイヌ文化と自然２》アイヌ文化における時間使用 高橋 靖以（北海道大学アイヌ・先住民研究センター博士研究員＝特別寄稿） 月刊シロㇿ]</ref>.
